IAM policies - CloudFormation and S3

manage access in AWS by creating policies adn attaching them to IAM identities (users, groups, roles), or AWS resources

policy: an object that is associated with an identity or resource, defines permissions

IAM principal (user or role) makes a request - AWS evaluates the policies

most policies stored as JSON documents 6 policy types:
 - identity-based
 - resource-based
 - permission boundaries
 - Organisations SCPs
 - ACLs
 - session policies
 
IAM policies define permissions for action regardless of method used to perfoem operation. e.g. if policy allows GerUser, a user with that policy can get user information from AWS Management COnsole, AWS CLI or API
is console access is allowed, an IAM user can sign in to the console using a user name and password, programmatic access allowed - user can use access keys to work with the CLI or API

